<change id=0115>
 <author> Tim Cornwell </author>
 <date> 2002/02/10 </date>
 <avers> 1.7 </avers>
 <area> Tool </area>
 <package> appsglish </package>
 <module> maker </module>
 <type> Code Documentation </type>
 <category> New </category>
 <defects>  </defects>
 <summary>
maker provides make functionality within Glish
 </summary>
 <description>

maker provides a closure interface to the Glish make_client. It can be used just as make is build a collection of related files. The example in the documentation shows how maker can be used to construct an image from a FITS file by invoking the steps in between. The make rules can be put in a makefile or specified from Glish.

Darrell did the hard part: the make client.
 </description>
</change>

<change id=0120>
 <author> Tim Cornwell </author>
 <date> 2002/02/25 </date>
 <avers> 1.7 </avers>
 <area> Tool </area>
 <package> appsglish </package>
 <module> executive </module>
 <type> Code Documentation </type>
 <category> New </category>
 <defects>  </defects>
 <summary>
Queueing and execution of scripts and commands
 </summary>
 <description>

The executive tool allows queuing and execution of scripts or commands. Each script or command is queued up and as appropriate executed in a glish client that may be running remotely. Facilities are present for killing running jobs and for deleting queued jobs. There is also an interface to allow make commands to be executeed easily.
 </description>
</change>
